<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (15): An empire-builder who
stalled - Industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NUFFIELD: A BIOGRAPHY by Martin Adeney Robert Hale Pounds 18.99, 224 pages
ANYONE WITH an interest in the decline and fall of British industrial power
must have regard to the motor industry and in particular to the story of
William Morris, the first Lord Nuffield.
In the late 1920s, the Oxford-based Morris and his Birmingham rival Austin
held 60 per cent of the British car market, prompting Edsel Ford, son of
Henry, to report to his father: 'We have been defeated and licked in
Britain.'
William Morris, the son of an Oxfordshire farmer, who started his business
life as a bicycle repair boy, was the man chiefly responsible for that state
of affairs. His intuitive grasp of popular taste, his mechanic's commitment
to building reliable machines, and his more surprising vigour in addressing
international trends in his industry, were the qualities that marked him
out.
Like the Japanese half a century later, Morris recognised that his early
designs and successes would count for nothing if others - notably Ford -
used more efficient production methods to offer lower prices. As early as
1913, with his company barely profitable, he crossed the Atlantic to study
American methods and to seek deals with American components manufacturers.
The result was the Morris Cowley and the Morris Oxford and the company's
projection, following the hiatus of the 1914-18 war, into the front rank as
a volume car producer.
In the heydays of the 1920s Morris continued to amass durable motor trade
insights. He was an early proponent of hire purchase and marketing devices
such as owners' clubs and more than any of his competitors he recognised
that his customers would be impressed by cars loaded with 'free' extras.
It is difficult to separate the reasons for the Morris company's subsequent
decline from an account of the man. Energetic and capable of vaulting
optimism, Morris also had an insecure and even paranoid side which prevented
him trusting senior colleagues or seeing the potential in alliances with
rivals. Most specifically, he fell out with the equally headstrong Leonard
Lord, who left Morris in 1936, after the founder had refused his demand for
a share in the company, to run Austin, where he vowed to undercut Morris at
every model launch and to take Cowley apart 'brick by brick.'
Morris's own inability to delegate was compounded and perhaps rendered fatal
by the circumstances of his time. In a country that had yet to recognise the
fading sunset hanging over the Empire, he allowed himself to be distracted
by the Australian market and the 'Empire' car project, which never got into
production. His attraction to politics, in which his bullying egoism scored
local successes, seems not to have nourished insight into global trends
between the wars.
Above all, he failed to see that his early success in building, for its
time, a lean production system was one that he would have to repeat again
and again in one lifetime if his achievement was not to perish. As Adeney
says, he was not so much a Victorian industrial paternalist as an Edwardian,
'a product of a more overblown age when much of the Victorian striving had
been replaced by a more complacent feeling that Britannia ruled the waves
and much of the world by right.' In the end, Morris was a management
failure.
Perhaps he sensed that he had moved out of his depth, even though he was not
a man to make such an admission. In the last 20 years of his life, before
his death in 1963, he devoted most of his attention to philanthropic work,
based upon the Nuffield Foundation. That was a role in which his autocratic
and irascible temper could be more easily accommodated and through which he
did much good. It also, however, yielded the irony that his acquired name,
Nuffield, would live longer, on the gate of an Oxford college, than his
family name in either the register of British corporations or upon the
bodywork of a British car.
</TEXT>
