<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (16): Hi-tech phrase book -
Industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BUSINESS DICTIONARY OF COMPUTERS by Jerry M Rosenberg John Wiley Pounds
39.95, 403 pages
SOME PEOPLE read dictionaries for fun, but it would take an uncommon turn of
mind to enjoy browsing through a dictionary of computing.
The Business Dictionary of Computers, however, is a useful addition to the
works of reference available to those who might need to know the meaning of
 -for example - disabled module, global variable symbol or sparse array just
once in a lifetime.
Written by Professor Jerry M. Rosenberg, of Rutgers University, it contains
definitions of 7,500 such phrases. It suffers from the usual
American-centred view of the business data processing world.
The Univac 1 is described as the first commercial electronic computer. No
mention of Leo, Ace or Atlas, alas.
</TEXT>
