<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (18): Finance in the new
Europe - Industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FINANCIAL INTEGRATION IN EUROPE by Harald A Benink Kluwer Academic
Publishers 202 pages
THE financial services industry in Europe probably faces a bigger challenge
than any other sector from the Single Market officially established at the
beginning of 1993. Whereas manufactured goods have travelled relatively
easily across borders in the past (though there are now even fewer
impediments), many providers of financial services - especially in the
retail markets - have until now found it almost impossible to penetrate
European frontiers, either because of regulatory barriers or daunting tax
obstacles.
Harald Benink, a Limburg University professor based, appropriately enough,
in Maastricht, sets out the legislative framework that will determine the
future shape of the EC's financial services industry. Most of this framework
is now in place - for banking and securities, for instance - but the life
assurance directive does not come into force until July 1994 and the pension
fund legislation appears stalled.
Financial institutions now face fundamental strategic decisions. Benink
warns, however, that they should not rush headlong into growth; in the US,
with a population about three-quarters that of the EC, banks have found
efficiency more important than size. He translates the US motto 'don't get
bigger, get fitter' into a European version: 'In any case get fitter, and if
necessary get bigger'.
Although an academic work, it may prove useful for commercial operators
looking for a volume that covers much of the detail of the EC's legal
structure for financial services.
</TEXT>
