<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (13): EC aid, why the cash
misses the mark - Trade
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LUBIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE EUROPEAN COMMUNITY AND THE DEVELOPING COUNTRIES by Enzo R Grilli
Cambridge Pounds 35, 387 pages
THE European Community is the world's biggest market, its greatest source of
development aid, and its largest contributor to the international financial
institutions.
All these superlatives would normally encourage you to think that developing
countries would get a good deal out of their relationship with the EC. Not
so, according to this useful book by Enzo Grilli. The EC's aid policies are
ineffective and uncoordinated; the trade preferences it grants to developing
countries are meagre and ungenerous.
Above all, Grilli says, the EC's policies towards developing countries have
been characterised by what he calls 'limping regionalism': an almost
exclusive concentration on sub-Saharan Africa and a handful of other
countries in the Caribbean and Pacific - the so-called ACP countries.
This geographical narrowness is the child of history. When the Community was
first set up in the late 1930s, the colonialists among its founder members -
Italy, Belgium, but above all France - managed to transfer the burden of
their colonial responsibilities to the new Community, in effect by
unilaterally attaching their colonies to the Treaty of Rome. What this did
was to create a free trade area which comprised not only the original six
Community members, but also the 22 colonies and territories owned by the
six.
This initial burst of international nepotism was reinforced in the following
decades, culminating in the 1975 Lome Convention, which widened the circle
of the chosen to include the former colonial possessions of the Community's
newest member, the UK. Lome was hailed for a time as a new model for
development cooperation, promising a large pool of aid resources as well as
other gifts such as export stabilisation funds and non-reciprocal trade
preferences. Subsequent renewals of the Lome agreements, however, attracted
progressively less enthusiasm.
Grilli suggests that the colonial-funded geographical focus of the
Community's efforts in the developing world intensified during the 1970s and
1980s, effectively ignoring Latin America and Asia. But all this might seem
fair enough - who can criticise the EC for paying too much attention to
countries in sub-Saharan Africa, the Caribbean and the Pacific, since it is
these countries that are most in need of aid? Who cares if Europe's motives
are straight out of Machiavelli, so long as the cheques get posted?
Things are not so simple. Grilli argues that the use of aid by Community
members as a bilateral political weapon allows serious questions to be
raised about the effectiveness of the aid, since it is disbursed in an
uncoordinated fashion with little regard for its economic benefits.
Moreover, the trade preferences that the EC grants have, it seems, done
nothing to prevent the economic decay of many developing countries, and
Grilli refers to studies which 'uniformly come to the conclusion that the
Lome Conventions failed to have any marked impact on ACP aggregate exports'.
Grilli's arguments about the nature of the EC's regionalism are compelling,
but he gives too little attention to how things might be changing. As
Africa's economic problems become more evidently malignant, the continent is
clearly losing its appeal for the Community's policy makers, especially now
that eastern Europe presents such an inviting claim on the EC's resources.
It is difficult to doubt the suggestion that eastern Europe will to some
extent replace Africa as the EC's 'region of choice.' It is perhaps a shame,
then, that this book was not written a year later, which would have allowed
more time to digest the emerging relationship between the EC and eastern
Europe, to show more clearly how the EC's regionalism is limping towards the
east.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
