<PROFILE>_AN-DFVCUAGXFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930622
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (11): Overtaken by events -
Trade
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL HOLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DOING BUSINESS IN SOUTH AFRICA edited by Jonathan Reuvid Kogan Page Pounds
25, 300 pages
SELDOM CAN a publisher's blurb have been more revealing. 'This book is about
South African business practice and opportunity - not politics.' The
priggish note evokes the old South Africa, and the school of thought which
held that apartheid, business and sport occupied different compartments.
If you want a learned account of the rules governing business entities and
their regulation in South Africa, or a discourse on financial reporting and
auditing, this book may be helpful. But anyone planning to do business in
the new South Africa, and seeking a hard-headed appraisal of risks and
opportunities, will be disappointed. They will need to look elsewhere for
advice - perhaps starting with the emerging breed of 'consultants' who
exchange their political credentials and their contacts book for a seat on
the board.
The no-politics rule seems to have kept out, for example, any analysis of
ANC economic policy other than complacent reassurance. 'Nationalisation is
no longer on the ANC agenda,' we are told in the book's introduction.
Certainly that is what Ready to Govern, the ANC policy document, says - but
while hedging its bets. A future democratic South Africa, says the document,
will consider:
Increasing the public sector in strategic areas through, for example,
nationalisation.
Reducing the public sector in certain areas in ways that will enhance
efficiency, advance affirmative action and empower the historically
disadvantaged.
The book's introduction also confidently asserts: 'Nor is the 'unbundling'
of the interconnected conglomerates which dominate much of South African
industry . . . seen any longer as a political priority.' Oops] Since that
was written Gencor has unbundled. 'Now one of the capitalists has broken
ranks,' commented the FT's correspondent in Johannesburg at the time, 'it is
no longer possible to dismiss unbundling as an airy Marxist fancy. Indeed,
it is likely that South Africa has only witnessed the dawn of an era of
significant corporate restructuring.'
And what of affirmative action to redress the apartheid legacy? The National
African Federated Chamber of Commerce, the black business federation (not
included in the book's mediocre contacts list), has demanded that all
companies listed on the Johannesburg Stock Exchange have 30 per cent black
board representation by 2000, that blacks hold 40 per cent of equity and 60
per cent of posts at all management levels. Unrealistic; but a sign of the
times that a really useful guide to business in the new South Africa would
have illuminated.
</TEXT>
<XX>
