<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (10): How to survive in a
competitive jungle - Trade
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MONTAGNON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BEYOND FREE TRADE: FIRMS, GOVERNMENTS AND GLOBAL COMPETITION edited by David
B Yoffie Harvard Business School Press Dollars 40, 466 pages
ANYONE WHO wants to understand the thinking behind President Clinton's more
aggressive approach to trade policy will find this book a help. Indeed, in
its quiet way it says quite a lot about the direction of the trade policy
debate generally.
For some time US opinion, which has tended to set the agenda in recent
years, has been moving away from the simple notion that comparative
advantage is all that matters and that the best policy is therefore to
ensure markets are open and unprotected. The realisation has grown that, for
certain industries, other things, such as regulation, matter as much, if not
more, to the direction of trade flows.
The starting point of this collective enquiry - it includes contributions
from nine separate authors - is that natural comparative advantage matters
only in the early stages of a product's life and for industries that are
highly fragmented. As industries become more concentrated - and entry
barriers grow - other forces swing into action. Decisions on location will
be taken with regard to what competitors are doing and shifts in government
regulation. Sometimes location decisions that no longer make particular
sense will not be reversed because companies suffer from inertia.
The thesis is tested with reference to a range of industries, from
semiconductors and computers to ball-bearings, mineral processing and
insurance. One conclusion is that as more companies compete head-to-head in
multiple international markets, the more they will gravitate towards similar
production locations, trade patterns and technical as well as managerial
capabilities. More interesting, though, is the underlying question of which
are best equipped to survive the process.
The book holds out one piece of advice for companies - that they need to
tackle their international and not just their domestic competition.
Caterpillar has emerged as one of the survivors in construction equipment,
but it had a tendency to worry too much about Dresser and too little about
Komatsu. Another conclusion of greater relevance for government policy is
that survivors benefit from a strong position in their domestic market.
The mistake the US made in telecommunications may have been to de-regulate
while other countries did not. Similarly the US has been more open than
other countries such as Germany and Japan to non-life insurance. As a result
its insurance industry suffers from intense price competition and damaging
cyclical swings. In Japan, where the industry is more regulated and local
companies control the distribution channels, the cycle is less vicious.
Domestic companies have a stronger base from which to expand
internationally.
One thus begins to see why US trade policy is so concerned with market
access. This is fine when it involves a genuine insistance on national
treatment - or regulatory policies that do not discriminate against
outsiders - and on international co-ordination of the de-regulation process.
This kind of question is likely to come up in the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade if and when it can finally lay the Uruguay Round to rest.
Competition policy could well be on the agenda of future rounds.
More worrying is the book's lack of emphasis on the multilateral framework.
In her chapter on semiconductor trade Laura d'Andrea Tyson, who is now
President Clinton's chief economic adviser, glosses over the fact that
aspects of the 1986 US semiconductor agreement with Japan were declared
illegal by the Gatt. The book conveys the impression that the agreement is a
fine example of a government policy directed at influencing the flow of
trade. Some US companies resumed production as a result of the agreement
while, albeit slowly, foreign penetration of the Japanese market increased.
It matters little to Ms Tyson that users of semiconductors in Europe were
forced to pay higher prices. That tendency towards bilateralism, however, is
a reason for the rest of the world to be careful. This book is good at
identifying the issues; it would be even better if it tried to pre-empt the
more dangerous conclusions.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
