<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / The FT Review of Business Books (5): The night the City
almost died - Finance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CEDAR STORY: THE NIGHT THE CITY WAS SAVED by Charles Gordon
Sinclair-Stephenson Pounds 18.99, 326 pages
ALMOST everybody has now forgotten the collapse 20 years ago of Cedar
Holdings, an obscure second mortgage company. But not Charles Gordon, a
well-connected one-time journalist turned minor financier who is the author
of this elegantly written, if distinctly self-indulgent, history of a
secondary bank which crashed on the dramatic night of Wednesday, December
19, 1973.
Whether a participant in a drama should write the history is a moot point.
Certainly there is an overdose of score-settling here by the author, who was
closely involved in setting up Cedar in the 1960s for the Morrison family,
one-time dress shop proprietors who wanted to move into the more glamorous
worlds of property and banking.
Charles Gordon fixed them up with respectable institutional partners such as
the Unilever pension fund and Phoenix Assurance but he was pushed off the
board in 1971. Jack Morrison's 'detestable' nephew assumed a leading role,
and the company began to tap the short-term money markets in order to
finance expansion. Then the family, disastrously for them as it was to turn
out, merged their property company Amalgamated Securities into Cedar, mainly
in order to gain family voting control of the combined enterprise. The top
executives were just trying out their brand new Hawker Siddeley 125/600B
corporate jet when the secondary banking crisis struck. With unbelievable
suddenness the family fortune was lost.
According to Gordon's account, the Morrisons failed to understand the risks
of one of Britain's regular credit bubbles. But as the reader wades through
pages of name-dropping, of accounts of irrelevant French Riviera parties,
and of remarks such as 'my driver was waiting patiently outside Wilton's', a
different conclusion emerges: that the shortsighted Gordon designed a
cultural clash into Cedar, and even an ethnic one, because this was very
much the story of upstart Jewish businessmen colliding with establishment
institutions. Much later, in the 1980s, the collision was to be echoed when
the Bank of England clashed awkwardly with the Pakistani-controlled BCCI.
So to that awful night at the Bank of England in late 1973, when the fact
that the Jewish Morrisons were served with ham sandwiches was the least of
their problems.
Although not himself a participant at this final stage of the story, Charles
Gordon has crafted an entertaining reconstruction. For the sake of the
financial system it was declared by the Bank that Cedar had to open its
doors the next day; but the institutions, in exchange for their willingness
to replace the money extracted by stampeding depositors, stripped the
company of its property assets and closed it for new lending business. In
the end the deal only went through, after 1 am, because the family was in a
minority on the board. The City was saved; Jack Morrison was broken, and
died four years later worth Pounds 6,500.
Reading at times like a kind of Pseud's Guide to the Barber property boom,
the book is liberally peppered with flattery and putdowns: Stash Radziwill
was 'the quintessential European aristocrat' but Kenneth Cork, the
liquidator, spoke in an 'upper-class cockney accent'. There is much, much
more about people than about Cedar Holdings, but perhaps that is as it
should be.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2731 Book Publishing.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Products &amp; Product use.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page III
</PAGE>
</DOC>
