<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / London Stock Exchange: Thorn strong
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON, JOEL KIBAZO and CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The market welcomed Thorn EMI's decision to sell its lighting business to
Investcorp, a Bahrain international investment bank, for Pounds 162m,
especially against the backround of an otherwise dull leisure sector. The
shares gained 25 at 920p - the company's first break ever through 900p - as
1.3m shares changed hands.
Traders saw the move as a step closer to Thorn's presumed goal of discarding
periferals to leave the company with two core businesses, music and rentals.
Thorn has sold about 60 firms since 1987 and now makes 82 per cent of
profits from music and rentals.
The market ultimately expects to see a demerger but was taken somewhat by
surprise by the long-expected move, which has been little discussed in
recent weeks.
A generally sluggish banks sector provided a bright spot in TSB, which moved
to an all-time high of 198p before finishing a net 2 up at 197p ahead of
interim figures scheduled for Thursday.
TSB is the first of the clearing banks to report their half-year numbers,
with Lloyds Bank due to follow at the end of next month.
Analysts' interim profits forecasts extend from around Pounds 50m to as high
as Pounds 130m, compared with last time's Pounds 92m, with provisioning
against bad debts expected to show an increase on the previous year's first
half but a fall on the second half's figure. NatWest Securities is
forecasting a 5 per cent increase in the interim dividend to 3.3p.
Turnover in British Steel rose to 19m shares after the board disclosed
losses that were lower than the market expected.
US selling early in the session prompted a decline in the shares to 96p, a
fall that was reversed with the release of the figures. However, analysts'
concern about steel overcapacity in the EC took hold in the afternoon,
bringing a further decline in the stock, which closed a touch harder on the
day at 98 3/4 p.
Shares in Rolls-Royce shed 2 1/2 to 147 1/2 p after trade of 5.5m on fears
that development costs for its new Trent-800 engine may be higher than
expected.
Worries about overcapacity in European steel also hurt ASW Holdings, which
gave up 8 to 205p.
Weekend press comment boosted Aerospace Engineering by 2 to 28p. Unconfirmed
talk of a broker's profits upgrading for BTR saw the shares advance 12 to
368p.
Grand Metropolitan moved up 12 to 426p on 6.7m shares traded ahead of an
analysts meeting. Analysts said the company continued to benefit from last
week's brokers' advice to sell Guinness in favour of GrandMet.
Food manufacturers were mostly firm, with Tate &amp; Lyle up 6 at 381p on news
that a strike at one of its American factories was over. Hillsdown, the
poultry to upholstery group, bucked the market trend to finish 5 off at 136p
United Biscuits, still riding a bid rumour, finished 8 higher at 408p. Once
again Cadbury Schweppes was tipped as the chief suspect.
The shares of bananas importer Geest continued to slide on traders' nerves
over the future of the European Community's banana regime, now the subject
of an inquiry by a panel of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade
(GATT). The stock ended 10 cheaper at 344p.
Other statistics, Page 32
</TEXT>
