<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow rallies on higher bonds
and dollar
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US SHARE prices staged a modest rally yesterday as equities, aided by firmer
bonds and a stronger dollar, rebounded from last Friday's futures and
options-related losses, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was 16.05 ahead at 3,510.82,
near its peak for the day. The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500
ended 2.54 higher at 446.22, but the Nasdaq composite was down 0.85 at
688.74. Trading volume on the New York SE amounted to 223.6m shares and
rises outnumbered declines by 1,124 to 818.
Last week ended with a steep loss on the Dow, incurred because of selling
linked to the monthly expiration of stock and stock index futures and
options, an event known as 'triple-witching'. Consequently, prices bounced
back at the opening yesterday in the traditional post-triple-witching rally,
with the Dow gaining 16 points in the first few minutes of trading.
Stocks, however, were unable to hold on to those gains and by early
afternoon, prices were either unchanged or, in the case of secondary issues,
firmly anchored in negative territory. Later in the day the market righted
itself once again, supported by a solid rise in bond prices - the benchmark
30-year bond rose half a point, in the process pushing the yield down to
6.77 per cent. Bonds were cheered by positive remarks about inflation from a
senior Federal Reserve official.
The Dow was aided in its recovery by a sharp turnround in Caterpillar
shares, which had fallen sharply in early trading, depressing the markets'
leading average. In spite of yesterday's gains, some analysts believe the
markets may have already settled into a narrow trading pattern for the
summer, and a period of relatively subdued activity.
Caterpillar initally fell more than Dollars 5 to Dollars 72 in hectic
trading after the company warned that its non-US business was weakening.
Later in the session, however, the price rallied to end a net Dollars 1 1/2
down at Dollars 75 3/4 on turnover of 1.1m shares.
Tambrands jumped Dollars 6 1/8 to Dollars 46 1/4 in heavy trading on reports
that the board is considering selling the company, which at the start of
trading yesterday had a market value of about Dollars 1.6bn. One of the
companies named as a possible buyer, Johnson &amp; Johnson, saw its shares slip
Dollars  5/8 to Dollars 42 1/4 .
Nike plunged Dollars 9 1/8 to Dollars 57 7/8 as investors got the first real
chance to react to Friday's news, announced after the market had closed,
that the sportswear maker expects its earnings for the year ending in May
1994 to fall significantly short of market expectations. The warning led to
a series of ratings downgrades by Wall Street brokers, further pummelling
the share price.
Reebok, Nike's main rival in the competitive sports shoe market, dipped
Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 29 3/8 in sympathy.
Canada
TORONTO price movements were mixed after a fair turnover. The TSE 300 index
ended 15.5 up at 3,922.4 but declines narrowly led advances by 358 to 351.
Volume totalled 55.5m shares valued at CDollars 612m.
Eleven of the 14 stock groups finished higher, the paper and forest products
group leading with a rise of 1.55 per cent.
</TEXT>
