<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: Polish copper combine lifts
output
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BOBINSKI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WARSAW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
POLAND'S KGHM state-owned copper producer has reported a Zl 1,415bn
(USDollars 81m) net profit for 1992 as output in the first five months of
this year is running 3.4 per cent higher than in the same period last year.
The combine's final results yesterday put KGHM's sales in 1992 at Zl
17,361bn while costs reached Zl 13,639bn. Last year the combine, sited in
western Poland, produced 387,000 tonnes of copper and 914 tonnes of silver.
The first five months of this year have seen copper output reach 171,000
tonnes, 3.4 per cent more than last year, when it rose by 2.3 per cent
despite a six week strike. In 1991, KGHM, where the trade unions are
resisting an attempt to sell a minority stake to foreign investors, reported
a Zl 900bn net profit, equivalent USDollars 82m at the present exchange
rates.
