<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / World Commodities Prices: Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
London COCOA prices continued last week's rally as the September contract
climbed towards Pounds 750 a tonne. New York's higher opening provoked a
spurt of buying interest in London in the afternoon, but traders attribute
the recent break-out mainly to technical factors. London robusta COFFEE
prices lost further ground in the afternoon as the market drifted back in
line with New York. Earlier hopes that prices might attempt to edge higher
faded quickly as New York opened lower. Both markets continued to disregard
talk of retention schemes among Latin American producers. 'How many times
have we heard this before? Anything that starts from outside an
international coffee agreement never takes off,' one trader said. On the LME
three-month COPPER was unable to hold above Dollars 1,900 a tonne after
advancing in early trading. But dealers said a further attempt is likely
today. Three-month ALUMINIUM was unable to reach the Dollars 1,215 a tonne
target, easing from its highs on the kerb with copper, but remaining
technically constructive. GOLD futures were trading near session lows at
midday on Comex.
Compiled from Reuters
</TEXT>
