<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / UK Company News: Acquisitions help JLI leap 64% - New
businesses contribute Pounds 1.16m to operating profits of Pounds 5.95m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THREE acquisitions helped JLI Group, the dried fruits, nuts and pickle
ingredients processor, lift pre-tax profits by 64 per cent, from Pounds
3.17m to Pounds 5.2m, in the year to March 31.
The group bought food processors TG Smith (Fine Foods) for Pounds 800,000 in
April and Cadec in June for Pounds 500,000, as well as packer and
distributor Brookerpaks for Pounds 2.5m in September.
Two rights issues in as many years, which raised Pounds 20.7m net, funded
the acquisitions. Gearing fell from about 33 per cent to 14 per cent and
interest payments to Pounds 734,000 (Pounds 940,000).
The new businesses contributed Pounds 1.16m to operating profits of Pounds
5.95m (Pounds 4.11m) and Pounds 20.4m to turnover of Pounds 104.7m (Pounds
84.3m). Operating margins climbed for the sixth successive year, reaching
5.7 per cent (4.9 per cent).
Earnings per share rose to 9.3p (8.8p, adjusted for the rights issues). The
final dividend is 3.1p giving a total of 4.65p (4.5p).
Mr Yoav Gottesman, chief executive, said: 'Our declared strategy is to
improve the quality of our business and earnings through the development of
higher margin, value added activities in food processing and distribution.'
He said the company was aiming to grow organically and through acquisition.
Devaluation of sterling will have an effect as the increase in relative raw
material prices collided with the competitive squeeze on retail prices.
The group said following the acquisitions its snacks division had 20 per
cent of the UK nut market. The snacks businesses were now integrated under
the renamed Tee Gee Snacks with a newly appointed managing director, Mr
Peter Clee.
In the ingredients division, Jack L Israel (Norfolk) and Langwoods, both
food processors, had a 'disappointing year' with selling prices depressed by
low fresh produce prices.
However, Jack L Israel's distribution business performed well and the
division benefited from acquisition.
</TEXT>
