<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / UK Company News: Allen hit by construction decline as
profits fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER PEARSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRE-TAX profits at Allen were halved from Pounds 3.21m to Pounds 1.51m in
the year to March 28 as the construction industry continued to decline,
undermined by high interest rates in the first half and 'political and
economic uncertainty' in the second. Turnover fell to Pounds 52.2m, against
Pounds 58.9m.
While announcing the results, Mr Donald Greenhalgh, chairman and managing
director of the group, which has interests in housebuilding, contracting,
hire services and property development and investment, inveighed against pay
rises for directors even when their companies have fallen into losses, long
service contracts and share options.
This time, Allen's six board directors shared Pounds 417,000 for basic
salaries, benefits in kind, and pension contributions, against Pounds
456,000 previously. Some Pounds 440,000 is expected for this year. Further,
main board directors received no performance-related bonuses (last time
Pounds 135,000 was paid), though Mr Greenhalgh said directors and staff of
particular companies were rewarded for meeting pre-set targets.
Margins in the housebuilding and hire services sides were hit as operating
profits declined 27 per cent to Pounds 1.47m and 45 per cent to Pounds
410,000 respectively. Their turnovers were more or less static at Pounds
15.9m and Pounds 7.8m respectively. Completed houses rose by 9 to 280.
Mr Ken Fox, deputy managing director, said that Allen had now left the
speculative development market, but that property investment was 'a steady
earner'.
Divisional profits tumbled to Pounds 42,000 (Pounds 150,000) on turnover of
Pounds 437,000 (Pounds 1.6m). Contracting made Pounds 780,000 (Pounds 1.5m)
on turnover down at Pounds 26.8m (Pounds 32.9m). After a one-off 25.9 per
cent tax charge, earnings per share only declined to 5.05p (9.69p), allowing
the maintained total dividend of 5p to be covered. The final is a proposed
3.35p.
</TEXT>
<XX>
