<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
For decades the received wisdom in Britain has been that American television
is rubbish but that, thanks to the Hollywood film tradition, they have a
flair for action drama series and also manage ensemble sitcoms quite well.
Yet in fact, from the days of 'The Twilight Zone', American television has
always been remarkably good at fantasy and science fiction, and although
British television succeeded with 'The Avengers' and 'Dr Who' in the 1960s,
it has not produced anything memorable in this category recently. The
American series Quantum Leap (9.00 BBC2) about a man who inhabits the bodies
of others, is unfortunately inconsistent. Dream On (11.35 C4) is a modern
American sitcom which does not depend upon ensemble playing but upon the
talents of Brian Benben. He plays a New York publisher with an extensive
fantasy life manifested mainly as memories of 1950s television series. This
programme nails another myth by being far more daring sexually than any
British comedy series. BBC1 goes back to 1975 for a memorable British
comedy: The Good Life (8.00) .
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
