<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Untitled item
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FROM EARLY morning meetings with officials to speaking at party engagements
until late into the evening, any senior minister has a lifestyle that
generates enormous pressure, Alison Smith writes.
Apart from the stress of office, however, there was nothing to suggest that
Mr Michael Heseltine would be a likely victim of a heart attack.
Mr Julian Critchley, Mr Heseltine's long-standing friend and his biographer,
told ITN yesterday: 'Michael scarcely drinks and in all the years I have
known him, he has not been interested in food very much. He eats anything
put in front of him. He certainly doesn't smoke.'
Colleagues added that his work on his arboretum on his estate on the
Oxfordshire-Northamptonshire borders probably contributes to giving him a
healthier lifestyle than that of many at Westminster.
The 60-year-old Mr Heseltine's political persona is that of someone relaxed
in the face of difficulties which are no worse than those that governments
have survived before.
In spite of that style, however, Mr Heseltine drives himself hard, and has
elements of workload not shared by all his colleagues.
He is a member of no fewer than 12 of the 27 known cabinet committees and
sub-committees which carry out much of the business of government, including
the key committees on economic and domestic policy and on defence and
overseas policy.
His ability to deal with media interviews means that when the government is
in difficulties he is constantly fielded to sound a note of reassurance.
And his continuing high profile on the constituency engagements circuit  -
stepped up in his time out of office from 1986 - also contributes to the
burden, requiring tiring hours on the road.
</TEXT>
