<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / Tories fear future without Heseltine: Alison Smith on how
the party might cope should it lose its most prominent 'left-winger'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DISMAY of shocked Tory MPs goes beyond the fact that for some weeks at
least one of the cabinet's most formidable operators would not necessarily
be there to handle the latest piece of political bad news.
What, asked some of them, if the trade and industry secretary decided to
resign?
If Mr Heseltine were to leave the government, his departure would leave Mr
John Major with difficulties well beyond even those of losing a senior
colleague and key adviser.
But a decision by Mr Heseltine to leave the government would still be deeply
demoralising for his party.
Any further cabinet re-shuffle would inevitably create tensions so soon
after the one which was supposed to last until next summer, perhaps
particularly given the lingering dissatisfaction with the limited scale of
the last set of moves.
It would create a feeling of instability, heightened by the expectation that
at some point before the next election Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign
secretary, is likely to want to leave the cabinet.
At a time when Tory party faction fighting continually breaks out into the
open, the prime minister's task in re-balancing his cabinet would be
particularly sensitive.
The right might well see the opportunity to break the 'stranglehold' by the
left of the party on the three economic departments of the Treasury under Mr
Kenneth Clarke, and Mr David Hunt at the Department of Employment, as well
as Mr Heseltine at the Department of Trade and Industry.
Although there are signs of economic recovery - and Mr Clarke's move to the
Treasury has put the government in a better position to make the most of
them - many Tory MPs still feel battered by recent events.
There are few senior ministers who can cheer them by launching such
effective attacks on the opposition that even divisions among Conservative
backbenchers fade into the background temporarily.
The government would also be left woefully short of heavyweights and those
with long political experience.
Mr Heseltine's reputation was tarnished by the the fiasco of the pits
closure programme, which last October that prompted the most significant
non-Maastricht Tory rebellion since the election, and resulted in a damaging
climbdown by the government.
But even so, his sheer political longevity has makes him a figure who could
not be replaced at a moment's notice.
</TEXT>
