<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / Humberside and N Yorks face axe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HUMBERSIDE and North Yorkshire counties would be abolished and replaced by
seven unitary local authorities under recommendations published yesterday by
the Local Government Commission for England.
Three of the authorities would revert to the ancient Yorkshire title of
Ridings.
But Lincolnshire's two-tier structure would remain intact, with the status
quo unchanged. The commission's four reports so far this year have in all
cases recommended abolishing county councils and replacing them with unitary
authorities.
Arguing for leaving Lincolnshire unchanged, Sir John Banham, chairman of the
commission, said: 'If it ain't broke, don't fix it.' If, as some district
councillors claimed, there was genuine popular feeling to replace the county
with unitary authorities, he would expect protests. Consultation would test
which view was correct.
Two of the new authorities being created out of Humberside are on the south
bank of the Humber and were in Lincolnshire before 1974.
The commission wants to call them North East Lincolnshire - founded on Great
Grimsby and Cleethorpes - and North Lincolnshire - based on Scunthorpe,
Brigg and Barton. But they would be unitary authorities, administratively
separate from Lincolnshire.
On the north bank of the river, the rest of Humberside would split into two
unitary authorities - the city of Kingston upon Hull and East Riding,
including Beverley, Goole and Selby.
North Yorkshire would be carved up into the city of York, West Riding
(Dales) - based on Harrogate and Skipton - and North Riding, into which the
commission has controversially pushed Richmond, Northallerton and
Scarborough.
</TEXT>
<XX>
