<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / Import surge from outside EC raises fears
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IMPORT VOLUMES from countries outside the European Community measured at the
underlying level rose sharply last month, reviving concerns that the trade
deficit might worsen in the later stages of a recovery.
Underlying import volumes, which exclude oil and erratic items such as gems
and aircraft, rose a seasonally adjusted 0.6 per cent in May compared with
April, the Central Statistical Office said yesterday.
Underlying export volumes to countries outside the EC slipped back slightly
in May, although they remain at high levels due to many UK manufactured
goods being more competitively priced after sterling's devaluation.
In terms of value, the overall trade account last month benefited from high
exports of erratic items and from a Pounds 5m surplus on non-EC oil trade -
the first for five years.
These trends pushed the trade deficit with non-EC nations to Pounds 769m
last month, down from a revised Pounds 901m in April and the lowest deficit
since September.
On an underlying basis, the trade deficit last month for nations outside the
EC was Pounds 846m, up from Pounds 785m in April. Figures for the EC are not
available yet. Statisticians are ironing out a new system for collecting the
data.
In volume terms, the underlying level of non-EC imports in the three months
ending May 31 was up 2.5 per cent compared with the previous three months,
and up 14 per cent on the same period last year.
On the same basis, exports in the most recent three-month period were up 6
per cent compared with the three months ending in February, and 12 per cent
up on a year ago. Last month underlying export volumes slipped 3 per cent on
a high April figure described as 'a bit of freak' by government
statisticians.
The better export performance in recent months led to a small Pounds 5m
surplus on trade with North America last month, and an Pounds 85m surplus in
April. This was against the trend of recent years which has normally
featured deficits on this part of the trade account.
In the three months to the end of May, non-EC exports of manufactured goods
totalled Pounds 11.42bn, 7 per cent up on the Pounds 10.67bn for the
previous three months. Over the same period imports of manufactured items
have fallen 2 per cent.
These developments have pushed down the trade deficit on such goods from
Pounds 2.23bn in the three months to the end of February to Pounds 1.25bn in
the latest three-month period. Even so, due to the steep increase in imports
in the past year, the deficit for the past three months still stands higher
than for any quarter last year except October-December.
Over the whole of last year the non-EC deficit on manufactured goods came to
Pounds 4.64bn, from Pounds 2.89bn the year before.
