<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / Bristol print sackings raised in European parliament
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND ADBURGHAM, Wales and West Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN INDUSTRIAL dispute at a Bristol printing company was raised in the
European parliament yesterday by Mr Ian White, the Labour MEP for Bristol
and Bath, as an example of what he said was one of a series of attacks on
the rights of workers in the UK.
One hundred and twenty two members of the GPMU print union were dismissed on
April 26 by the family company of JW Arrowsmith after voting for industrial
action in pursuit of a Pounds 6.50 a week pay rise.
They were subsequently sent letters offering re-engagement at their previous
levels of pay but were told that the company would no longer recognise the
union and there would be personal contracts.
Since then only six workers have been re-employed and the company, founded
in 1854, has been picketed by the dismissed staff.
The union says the average length of service is 20 years. Mr John Price, a
union branch official, said: 'It is an old family firm with loyalties you
don't find in big companies. It has been a very flexible workforce and this
is their reward.'
Mr White yesterday presented a petition signed by the sacked workers to the
European parliament together with a written declaration condemning the UK
government for allowing such action by employers. 'This is not just an
isolated incident,' he said. 'The problems at Arrowsmith's are just part of
a series of attacks on the rights of workers in the UK.'
He said the practice of derecognition of trade union negotiation procedures,
and the issuing of individual employment contracts, set UK workers apart 'as
potentially the most exploitable in the community'.
Miss Victoria Arrowsmith-Brown, chairman and managing director, said the
company had suffered since January from an unofficial overtime ban before
the industrial action vote was taken.
She said neither the union nor the chapel (local union branch) had behaved
responsibly. 'I think the chapel's view was: 'We have to have a wage
increase, never mind whether the company can afford it'.'
JW Arrowsmith, which mainly prints technical journals, says it has suffered
from the recession and made a loss of Pounds 201,000 last year on a turnover
of Pounds 4.6m.
Miss Arrowsmith-Brown said that because there had not been a good return to
work after the dismissals, the company had restructured itself with a much
smaller staff. It employed 55 people, and did not expect to increase that
above 65 or 70. 'For us, it is no longer a dispute. There is no resolution
to be achieved.'
</TEXT>
