<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / Cleaning up with orange peel
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DISCARDED orange peel, especially from Brazil, has turned out to have
astonishing powers as an industrial solvent and cleanser. It may replace one
of the chemicals doing most damage to the ozone layer, which the world's
governments have agreed to ban by 1995.
The solvent, called Pronatur, cleans stubborn materials such as oil and
bitumen from any surface, including human skin, but is so safe it can be
drunk - although this is not recommended: it might smell like oranges, but
it tastes ghastly.
It is made from a blend of natural oils squeezed from orange peel from
around the world. Because there is no scientific breakthrough to patent the
blend is being kept secret, as are the names of most of the countries the
oranges come from, although Brazilian peel is an important source of oil.
Oranges, it appears, have locally determined natural chemicals in their
zest.
Bulked out with an inert paraffin, the product sells at Pounds 2 a litre.
Edward Billington &amp; Sons, a Liverpool sugar merchant and food company, has
spent more than Pounds 250,000 setting up a plant in Bootle to make 1m
litres a month.
The product was developed by Mr Richard Manbiot when he worked for
Glenmarkie, a small Aberdeen solvent manufacturer. He and Mr Paul
Richardson, a colleague, were negotiating to buy the company from its owner,
but were hesitant about the risks of borrowing the necessary Pounds 750,000.
Impressed with the potential of Pronatur and related solvents, Billington -
a customer - has bought the rights to the products and set up a subsidiary
with equity stakes for Mr Manbiot and Mr Richardson.
Mr Manbiot said yesterday: 'This is a low-tech solution to a high-tech
problem. EC countries use 113,000 tonnes of 1,1,1-trichloroethane a year and
have agreed to ban it by 1995 under the Montreal protocol because of the
damage done to the ozone layer after it evaporates.
'I'm a cook rather than a chemist. I developed Pronatur by trial and a lot
of error. Then it was matter of working out how to scale up for mass
production. We reckon we have a two-year lead on the rest of the world.
Citrus has always had grease-cutting power. This stuff maximises it.'
Trials have proved Pronatur is good at cleaning up oil slicks. It absorbs
the oil immediately, forming a solution that mixes in water and floats on
top of it.
'You then skim or vacuum it off. If you drag an oil-absorbing polyester
cloth across it, you can even cart it all off in plastic bags and burn it
safely,' Mr Manbiot said.
The solvent is being used in hospitals to dissolve bitumen splashes off the
burns they cause, reducing further damage to tissue.
It takes 30 times longer than conventional solvents to evaporate, so less
needs to be used. Most solvents waste 90 per cent of their power by
vaporising before they can act - aggravating pollution.
The new solvent has been endorsed by the Department of Energy as category 1,
meaning it is ideal for a wide range of cleaning purposes. The Ministry of
Agriculture, Fisheries and Food has approved it for use in oil spillages.
It already has approvals from Powergen, Nuclear Electric, British Gas,
Eastern Electric, Rolls-Royce Aerospace, ABB Transport, South Wales Electric
and Scottish Power. Mr Manbiot said: 'We have all the approvals needed for
this to be a window of opportunity to break into bigger markets.'
When Pronatur breaks down it forms safe carbon dioxide. That means it should
also score over the alternative to 1,1,1-trichloroethane, trichloroethylene,
which is toxic when inhaled.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Edward Billington and Sons.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2842 Polishes and Sanitation Goods.
    P2869 Industrial Organic Chemicals, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
