<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / Engineering pay awards fall sharply
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORE THAN one in five engineering workers in South Yorkshire and the north
Midlands have accepted pay freezes in the past 12 months, the Sheffield
Association of the Engineering Employers' Federation said yesterday.
In the year ended May 31, about 22 per cent of the 350 companies in the
association negotiated pay freezes. More than 40 per cent settled for pay
rises of up to 2 per cent. Although a quarter settled at between 3.1 per
cent and 4 per cent, nearly all those were concluded almost a year ago.
Nationally, engineering industry pay settlements were about 8 per cent in
mid-1991. Recession and a climate of falling inflation has reduced demands
sharply since then.
Mr Nicholas Kemp, director of the association, said: 'The number of
companies settled at no increase is significant. It demonstrates managements
and employees are well aware that the current trading is still very
difficult, despite some indications of a slow recovery.'
