<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / CBI urges job advice 'credits'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Confederation of British Industry yesterday called for a new system of
'credits' for careers guidance.
It said such a system would allow individuals in England and Wales to 'buy'
guidance from Training and Enterprise Councils. Tecs in turn would have to
apply to the government for funding to provide careers guidance.
Mr Howard Davies, CBI director-general, said credits 'will encourage a true
market in advice, raising standards across the country'.
He also called for a system of minimum entitlements which would give women
returning to work, redundant workers, the long-term unemployed and
ex-offenders access to careers guidance.
The report also includes a call for improved quality, to be nurtured by the
creation of an advisory National Council for Careers Guidance to set
national standards, and for improved training of careers practitioners.
It says that fewer than one-third of careers teachers in schools have
professional qualifications. This puts the UK behind other countries.
A Credit to Your Career - An Employers' View of Education and Guidance. CBI
Publications, 103 New Oxford Street, London WC1A 1DU. Pounds 10 for members,
Pounds 15 non-members.
