<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / BMA to compile GP survival guide
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FAMILY DOCTORS have instructed the British Medical Association to draw up a
'comprehensive survival guide' for general practitioners who may wish to
stop providing National Health Service treatment.
A motion calling for the preparation of the guide was adopted at a
conference of the BMA's general medical services committee, which represents
family doctors, last week. It was passed against the advice of the BMA
leadership.
The immediate cause of concern, expressed in the motion, is the possible
implication for GPs of the government's proposed re-organisation of health
services in London. This envisages employing some family doctors on direct
NHS contracts - GPs are currently independent contractors - and the possible
involvement of the private sector in primary healthcare services.
BMA leaders believe, however, that the success of the motion also reflects a
wider and growing frustration among GPs and hospital doctors about salaries
and conditions of service. In such circumstances a threat to stop providing
NHS treatment is the doctors' ultimate sanction.
Doctors are, like other public sector employees, waiting to see whether the
government decides to continue a version of its 1.5 per cent pay ceiling for
a second year. If the ceiling is abandoned, the BMA plans to make
representations to the doctors' and dentists' pay review body that medical
earnings suffered in relation to other professions in the 1980s.
With the move to locally-managed trust hospitals under the 1991 NHS reforms,
it is now uncertain how long review body-recommended national pay scales for
hospital doctors will remain in existence.
Mr Chris Wilson, human resources director of Homewood NHS Trust, Surrey  -
which has pioneered the introduction of local contracts - told the National
Association of Health Authorities and Trusts conference last week that pay
accounted for about 70 per cent of a trust's costs. 'Any organisation that
says it is not interested in how 70 per cent of its resources are being used
is probably being quite irresponsible.'
</TEXT>
