<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / Bosses stand firm on political gifts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH COMPANIES helping to bankroll the Conservative party appear unlikely
to alter their attitudes towards political donations in the wake of the
frenzy over party funding which has hit Westminster.
The latest allegations involving Mr Asil Nadir do not seem to have shaken
the resolve of Britain's big corporate battalions, many of which continue
unquestioningly to support the Tories with hard cash.
According to a poll yesterday among 40 of Britain's largest contributors to
the Conservative Party, attitudes to the issue of political contributions do
not appear about to change. The message from corporate donors was that their
freedom to contribute - last year business gave Pounds 19m to Conservative
Central Office - and the accompanying rules, are quite clear. Companies say
that if attitudes change it will be because they no longer believe in the
values and virtues of the Tories.
It is up to the Tory party, say many of the biggest contributors, to devise
a system which leaves the organisation and its fund-raising activities well
above suspicion.
But the provision of shareholders' funds in return for unquantified but
presumed corporate - or even personal - reward may now be heading for a
radical overhaul, whatever party grandees may say. Little-publicised moves
to improve not only the efficiency but the transparency of the Tory party's
funding activities are under way and should be complete in time for the
party conference in the autumn.
Many companies yesterday stressed that the statutory obligations on them to
declare political donations were clear. They acknowledged that the
motivation for offering support varied and some believed that the
controversy would remain until state-funding enabled parties to turn their
back on other sources of funds.
While the Confederation of British Industry says the issue of contributions
is for members only and 'not something on which we have taken a view or are
likely to', the Institute of Directors emphasises that the 'law on company
disclosure is as watertight as you can get. We are not looking for any
changes'.
The view is shared by Mr Christopher Haskins, chairman of Northern Foods, a
Labour supporter but whose company makes no party contributions. He says the
law already makes company contributions transparent but would favour a
mandatory requirement on political parties to disclose contributions above
Pounds 10,000 to catch gifts by individuals, foreigners and private
concerns.
The idea that cash contributions directly assisted the donors was,
predictably, rejected by all the companies. Some said they expected other
contributors might believe that to be the case but their own motives were
usually a matter of supporting a philosophy.
One of the largest insurance groups said: 'We stopped contributions last
year. They were a hangover from the days when we feared nationalisation,
which is now a non-runner.'
Mowlem, the construction group, said donations might improve access to
government but did not offer any more influence. 'Neither is there any
evidence that honours follow contributions.'
One of Britain's biggest drinks companies, however, said that big donors
probably expected honours to follow. Companies, it said, should be compelled
to reveal all indirect contributions.
P&amp;O, the transport and shipping group headed by Lord Sterling, said its own
contributions to the Tories - Pounds 100,000 last year - had failed to
influence government policy. It cited the case of fines imposed for carrying
illegal immigrants on its ferries when it had not been given the authority
to inspect passports.
Sir Robert Clarke, chairman of United Biscuits, summed up the view of most
chief executives in saying his company - which paid Pounds 130,000 to the
Tories last year - had continued to help the party because it offered the
best economic climate. He would, however, strongly support state-funding for
parties.
Central Office's plans for changing its fund-raising approach include the
establishment of a board of treasurers, working alongside the existing board
of finance, charged with overseeing fund-raising.
It will be chaired by Mr Charles Hambro, whose 10-strong team - drawing
heavily on volunteer chief executives from the private sector - is expected
to be at work 'very soon'. More detailed party accounts - though they will
not include details of donors - are expected before the party conference in
October.
Sir Norman Fowler, party chairman, has already laid the ground-rules for
fund-raising, telling Mr Hambro that the exercise must ensure donors are
exclusively motivated by their wish to sustain a party championing free
enterprise.
Mr Paul Judge, the party's new director general, said recently the new
system was to ensure 'there are no nooks and crannies unchecked in terms of
finding those people who might want to support us'.
</TEXT>
