<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / NHS trusts 'slow to change'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOST National Health Service trusts have not introduced local pay setting,
single-union deals, or changes in the skill mix of health workers, according
to a comprehensive survey by Industrial Relations Services.
The research organisation, which received detailed responses from 33 out of
the 160 first- and second-wave trusts, found that some staff working for 80
per cent of the respondents were on local terms, but they were mainly
managers or specific occupational groups like healthcare assistants.
Some analysts argue that a crucial element in the government's health
reforms is the more effective use of labour, with local managers breaking
away from the Whitley system of national pay bargaining.
'Lack of management time and resources' is the reason most frequently given
in the survey for caution in making change, with the 1.5 per cent government
limit on public sector pay also mentioned as a disincentive.
Slightly more trusts have cut staff than increased it (12 and 10
respectively) since gaining self-governing status and over 40 per cent of
respondents expect staff numbers to fall in the next 18 months.
The biggest changes have been in the area of disciplinary procedures with
over three-quarters of trusts in the survey signing new agreements.
Only two trusts have derecognised any unions and single-union deals were
rare, though most respondents had 'single-table' bargaining.
Performance-related pay was mainly restricted to management level.
The European Community-inspired Tupe regulations, which govern the pay and
conditions of some staff transferred to trusts, have affected about
one-third of the trusts in the survey.
Industrial Relations review and report 537. Details from IRS, 18-20 Highbury
Place, London N5 1QP.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
