<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / European consumer defies the norm
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Community is still a long way from producing the homogenous
Euro-consumer, according to a mammoth study into consumer spending and
quality of life conducted across most of the EC's largest markets.
Patterns of consumer spending still vary considerably across Belgium,
Britain, France, Germany, Italy, the Netherlands and Spain - the countries
that account for 93 per cent of the EC's 340m consumers. The study finds
that the European drinks market is still characterised by national
distinctions. While the average per capita spending on alcohol, soft drinks
and other beverages (such as coffee and tea) consumed in the home was Ecu277
(Pounds 218) in 1992, Belgians spent 2.5 per cent more (Ecu455) than the
Italians or Spanish. The 16-volume report, published by Mintel, discloses a
wide range of similar discrepancies.
The Dutch spend almost 10-times more than the British on health-care
products; Italians spend Ecu950 each year on clothing, whereas Spaniards
spend just Ecu647; Germans spend more than 25 per cent of disposable income
on rent, fuel and power, against 12.8 per cent by Spaniards.
European Lifestyles 1993, available from Mintel, 18-19 Long Lane, London
EC1A 9HE. 16 volumes at Pounds 6,660.
</TEXT>
