<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / The Copenhagen Summit: Signs of a split in Bosnian
presidency
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT MAUTHNER, Diplomatic Editor and AGENCIES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BOSNIAN President Alija Izetbegovic is coming under pressure, not only from
the European Community but also from other members of the joint Bosnian
presidency to adopt a less hostile attitude to the latest proposals for the
country's political framework.
Arriving in Zagreb last night with Mr Haris Silajdzic, his foreign minister,
the president went straight for talks with the collective Bosnian
presidency, which includes Serbs and Croats as well as Moslems. Earlier in
the evening, the presidency had met in his absence, as signs emerged of a
split which could threaten his position as leader.
The presidency was reported to be trying to decide whether the
Moslem-dominated Bosnian government should join negotiations with Serbs and
Croats on dividing Bosnia along ethnic lines.
Before flying from Copenhagen yesterday, Mr Izetbegovic was ambivalent about
whether he would take part in future Geneva peace negotiations. He spoke of
the need to consult his government and parliament, adding: 'But we shall
never participate in negotiations which are a cover for further territorial
aims of the Serbs.'
Now that the international mediators, Lord Owen and Mr Thorvald Stoltenberg,
have conceded that the original Vance-Owen plan is defunct and that other,
if less desirable, avenues must be pursued, Mr Izetbegovic is seen by a
growing number of western diplomats as the main obstacle to progress. His
political demise would not be felt as a tragedy in western capitals.
After last week's meeting in Geneva of the presidents of Serbia, Montenegro,
Croatia and Bosnia, under the chairmanship of the mediators, separate talks
were held by the mediators with members of Bosnia's collective presidency.
At these talks, Mr Izetbegovic's colleagues adopted a more open attitude
than their leader to proposals for creation of three ethnic mini-states
within a loose confederal framework, which are due to be presented in detail
by Serbia and Croatia in Geneva tomorrow, according to western diplomats.
The extent of the split in the Bosnian presidency was underlined yesterday
by Mr Fikret Abdic, generally regarded as a moderate Moslem and potential
leadership challenger, who said no plans should be rejected outright. He was
quoted by Croatian radio as saying: 'Not one idea of the future arrangements
for Bosnia should be rejected.'
Lord Owen, while still insisting that the Bosnian Serbs must withdraw from
some territory they have occupied, has stressed that the situation on the
ground must be taken into consideration in any peace settlement.
However, he hopes to save some essential elements of the Vance-Owen plan,
such as demilitarisation of Bosnia, creation of a pluralistic democracy
through free elections and the guarantee of human rights. Most EC foreign
ministers have stressed that any peace settlement must be approved by all
the parties involved, and that Bosnia must remain a separate sovereign
state.
</TEXT>
