<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / British Steel condemns state support for European rivals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE WAR of words over the future of Europe's steel industry intensified
yesterday when British Steel attacked state subsidies for its Spanish and
Italian rivals and urged the European Commission to press ahead with
restructuring plans.
As British Steel reported its worst annual results since its 1988
privatisation - a pre-tax loss of Pounds 149m for the year to April 3 - Mr
Brian Moffat, chairman and chief executive, said the balance sheets of many
continental European steelmakers were 'in ruins'.
He singled out the Spanish and Italian industries as 'the worst offenders'
on subsidies and said British Steel and the UK government were both 'utterly
against' further job cuts in the UK.
Mr Moffat's outspoken comments come a year after British Steel closed its
Ravenscraig steelworks in Scotland. The company said no large
rationalisations were planned this year.
Mr Moffat warned, however, that if state subsidies continued elsewhere in
Europe, British Steel did not have unlimited funds. 'At the extremity this
could bring about further job losses,' he said.
The loss announced yesterday was expected by analysts. It compares with a
Pounds 55m deficit in 1991-92 and profits of Pounds 733m in 1989-90 when the
steel industry was booming.
British Steel's shares were privatised at 125p, and have traded as low as
54p this year. But they have recently recovered, helped by US buying, and
closed  1/4 p up yesterday at 98 3/4 p.
The company, which has already passed its interim dividend for 1992-93, cut
its final dividend from 1.5p to 1p a share. Mr Moffat warned that
reinstating payouts to more normal levels would require 'a sustained
recovery in profitability'.
He stressed that the key to this was increased prices, which in turn
depended on the EC restructuring plans. British Steel has already raised
prices twice this year and Mr Moffat said: 'We will put up prices again at
the first commercially available opportunity.'
The main plank of the EC restructuring is a partly self-financed scheme
under which companies remaining in the industry would pay rivals to cut
capacity or leave the business. The EC has identified about 30m tonnes of
surplus hot-rolling capacity in the Community.
British Steel supports the plan, but is worried that unless subsidies are
eliminated by the Commission and member states, efficient private sector
producers will be forced to cut capacity further, while weaker but
state-supported enterprises are sustained.
Mr Moffat said the industry's problems could be resolved if significant cuts
in capacity were achieved. British Steel, which had the lowest costs and the
strongest balance sheet among west European steelmakers, was 'in a good
position to benefit from a successful outcome'.
Lex, Page 24
British Steel results, Page 26
London stocks, Page 44
</TEXT>
