<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUN 93 / EC leaders differ on how to revive growth and jobs: Delors
mandated to produce action plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   COPENHAGEN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EUROPEAN Community leaders last night drafted a broad strategy for dealing
with the unemployment crisis in the EC, providing a mandate for Mr Jacques
Delors to produce an action plan by the end of the year.
But at a summit in Copenhagen dominated by the worsening economic outlook
and a widespread feeling that high German interest rates are prolonging the
recession, EC leaders could do little to disguise differences on how to
revive European growth and employment.
Mr John Major, the prime minister, called for a fundamental rethink of the
Community's approach to job creation, stressing the need for more
liberalised labour markets, lower social costs for business and tighter
constraints on wage increases.
Warning that Europe's competitiveness had been dangerously eroded, Mr Major
repeated Britain's view that the social chapter in the Maastricht treaty
would amount to a 'job destruction programme'. He told his colleagues: 'Our
total labour costs are too high. Our employment markets are too rigid. And
our labour force is not adaptable and mobile.'
In a performance at the summit designed to demonstrate to his own critics in
the Tory party that Britain can now seize the initiative in Europe, Mr Major
suggested that there was a growing acceptance across the EC that it must
focus on improving its competitiveness with the rest of the world.
Mr Delors, president of the European Commission, conceded that Europe had
fallen far behind the US and Japan in its ability to create jobs. But he
rejected moves to dismantle Europe's social welfare system in favour of a
more deregulated labour market along US lines.
Mr Niels Helvig Petersen, foreign minister of Denmark which holds the EC
presidency until the end of the month, said the US model produced 'very
severe defects in the economy', as well as social problems, crime and
hopelessness in large urban areas.
However, Mr Felipe Gonzalez, Spain's Socialist prime minister, who narrowly
secured re-election against strong conservative opposition, came out in
favour of deregulation of labour markets.
'The recession is colliding with great rigidity in the labour market; we
have to get greater labour mobility,' he said, calling for more opportunity
for part-time work. Mr Gonzalez's remarks underlined how Europe's jobs
crisis is encouraging fresh thinking, even though EC leaders remain
undecided on how far to go.
'All the leaders see they are in trouble,' said a Dutch diplomat. 'This is
important because it is the start of the debate.'
Although most EC leaders indicated they would give Mr Delors a mandate to
produce a white paper on unemployment by the end of the year, Chancellor
Helmut Kohl of Germany argued that the Twelve could not wait until the next
EC summit in December in Brussels. He called on national governments to come
forward with ideas within four to six weeks.
The philosophical nature of the debate was mixed with a desire for
short-term action. The UK, Spain, France and Italy, among others, all called
for a co-ordinated drop in European interest rates - a move diplomats
interpreted as pressure on the Bundesbank to lower market rates.
Mr Delors said the size of the cut was not as important as the timing. 'We
are in a hole,' said an aide. 'A cut in interest rates is urgent.'
During the afternoon session Mr Delors also put forward several new measures
to produce short-term relief for the unemployed.
These include an extra Ecu3bn (Pounds 2.35bn) extension to the temporary
lending facility already provided by the European Investment Bank. This
would be in addition to the Ecu5bn agreed at last December's EC summit in
Edinburgh.
COPENHAGEN SUMMIT
Page 2
Major fires broadside at social policy
Delors makes a hit by aiming lower
Interest grows in stability pact plan
Editorial Comment, Page 23
Lex, Page 24
</TEXT>
