<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 93 / Foreign Exchange and Money Markets: Powerful dollar
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AFTER an extraordinary day of trading in currency markets on Friday, dealers
will now look for indications that the dollar can push further ahead against
the D-Mark and the Japanese yen, writes James Blitz.
On Friday, the dollar convincingly broke through the critical DM1.67 level
against the D-Mark, which some technical analysts have seen as the last
milestone before DM1.80 is reached.
The dollar's rise is mainly due to expectations that Germany will cut short
term interest rates soon. And, because of this, the M3 figures for money
supply growth, due out today or tomorrow, are important.
The M3 figure will indicate whether money supply is falling within the
Bundesbank's target range. If it does, the Bundesbank may ease its repo rate
on Wednesday for the first time in six weeks - and this will further reduce
the premium on holding D-Marks as opposed to dollars.
On the dollar side of the equation, Wednesday's durable goods figures for
May will show whether the US economy has recovered any further. A second
revision of the poor first quarter GDP figure is also due on the same day.
On Friday, the Japanese yen fell by around 3 per cent against the dollar
following the resignation of Mr Kiichi Miyazawa's government. Japanese
political developments will be watched closely, as dealers wait for any
reversal in the yen's prospects. The yen may be underpinned by the huge
Japanese trade surplus, despite the shock of Friday's fall.
The D-Mark's strength in Europe will be tested this week if more European
governments cut interest rates. There is strong speculation that the Bank of
France could cut its intervention rate today, following the Franc's strong
performance last week.
</TEXT>
