<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 93 / Guidance round the insider minefield
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A LEADING UK stockbroking firm has warned that if listed companies retreat
into their shells because of recent insider trading scares, they could risk
'an ill-informed market from which no-one benefits'.
A report by Hoare Govett Corporate Finance says that companies should
monitor market expectations. If there are material changes in trading, they
should consider making a formal Stock Exchange statement.
Fears that companies will clam up have followed the public censure of London
International Group by the Stock Exchange and the separate conviction of the
analyst Mr Thorold Mackie of insider trading offences following a private
meeting with a company. In May LIG told 13 analysts and four institutions
that profits forecasts for the company were too high.
Last week NFC, the transport group, said it might drop its 'best view'
forecasts of future profits because of concern about methods of
communicating information to shareholders.
Hoare's report was written to provide companies with guidance on how to
maintain contacts with the market within the present rules.
It says companies should make more use of the formal opportunities provided
by results announcements and annual meetings to set out their views on
current trading. 'This will provide a backdrop against which subsequent
informal communication with market participants can take place.'
It also advocates that where there is concern about a company's financial
position, it should consider releasing a balance sheet and a cash-flow
statement at the interim stage. This information could then be discussed
more freely.
The City tradition of year-end company briefings with analysts is 'unlikely
to be satisfactory in the new disclosure environment,' says Hoare. It points
out that companies could make formal trading statements either before the
closed season or after an important sales period, such as Christmas for
retailers.
Companies should develop a clear understanding of price-sensitive issues and
monitor market expectations carefully, Hoare says. If the need arises for
market perceptions to be changed, a public announcement should be made
promptly.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
