<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 93 / EC urged to act on jobs crisis: Summit faces calls for lower
interest rates and tough Asian trade policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER and HILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   COPENHAGEN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EC LEADERS open a two-day summit today under growing pressure to deal with
the unemployment crisis in the Community, including calls by participants
for a co-ordinated reduction in European interest rates and a tougher trade
policy toward Asia.
Spain and France are leading the pressure for new steps to stem the growing
tide of unemployed, expected to top 18m this year. But the Danish presidency
of the EC  - supported by the UK and Germany  - is holding firm against
protectionist measures which supporters say will safeguard jobs in Europe.
Trade is likely to be the most divisive issue at the Copenhagen summit,
which will also endorse proposals to integrate six former communist
countries in eastern and central Europe into the EC. EC leaders will also
discuss how to salvage something from the collapse of the international
peace initiative in Bosnia.
Mr Poul Nyrup Rasmussen, Danish prime minister, declared that the summit
would mark a 'turning point', now that ratification of the Maastricht treaty
was complete in Denmark and drawing closer in the UK. He was speaking after
a Socialist leaders' meeting called for a co-ordinated reduction in European
interest rates, warning that the Community risked a social explosion without
fresh measures to promote growth. The Danish prime minister offered little
prospect that EC leaders would reach any agreement beyond a general
exhortation on the need for greater economic policy co-ordination and public
investment. On the call for lower interest rates, he cautioned about
possible negative reaction from the markets and opposition from the German
Bundesbank.
Mr John Major, the prime minister, last night endorsed calls for lower
European interest rates but emphasised that Britain did not have high
borrowing costs.
In a clear reference to the effect of German rates on those countries whose
currencies remain in the European exchange rate mechanism, he said: 'That
Europe as a whole would benefit from lower interest rates I think is beyond
doubt, but that is a matter which must be discussed among those who find
themselves locked together.'
In his presentation today, Mr Jacques Delors, Commission president, is
expected to reject a retreat from the European welfare state. An aide said:
'He will focus not on whether to keep the European system of social
protection, but how.'
Mr Major is expected to attack what he perceives as unnecessary employment
costs, such as the Maastricht treaty's social chapter. EC diplomats
predicted friction if Mr Major pushed his case for greater deregulation too
hard, or if he sounded a triumphalist note now that the EC is reconsidering
social policies it supported in the more upbeat economic period before the
signing of the Maastricht treaty.
Along with Chancellor Helmut Kohl of Germany, Mr Major is also likely to
oppose calls from France for limited protectionism and urge leaders to renew
efforts to reach a Gatt Uruguay Round agreement by the end of the year.
EC concedes Bosnian peace plan is in tatters Page 2
Europe's jobs crisis Page 3
The Week Ahead Page 8
Streamlining the European Commission Page 17
Samuel Brittan Page 17
Editorial Comment Page 17
</TEXT>
