<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 93 / The Lex Column: Eurotunnel
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The time has come for Eurotunnel to break the impasse bedevilling its
relationship with its builders. The disagreement over Pounds 1.4bn of cost
over-runs has already besmirched the reputations of both parties. It is now
in danger of inflicting real financial damage too. Eurotunnel's
shareholders, who are unlikely to receive a dividend until the next century
anyway, will be severely disadvantaged if the tunnel's opening is delayed
further. With huge debts to be serviced, Eurotunnel's bankers cannot remain
disinterested.
Despite the heated rhetoric, the difference between the two parties may not
be great. At one stage, Eurotunnel was prepared to pay Pounds 1.2bn in paper
and cash. The outstanding disputed sum may be less than the revenues lost
because of delays in opening. Eurotunnel would be unlikely to recoup the
difference through separate litigation for damages from the contractors for
late opening. It has already reduced its projected revenues for 1994 by
Pounds 244m. That may yet prove too optimistic.
An agreement would benefit both parties. Eurotunnel could achieve a phased
opening of services and obtain operating licences faster than currently
predicted. The 10 contractors, some of which are strapped for cash, would
receive their money earlier. This week, Eurotunnel's shareholders can air
their views at the annual general meeting. Some seem prepared to challenge
their board's stance questioning whether the game is worth the candle. They
are surely right to do so.
</TEXT>
