<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 93 / The Lex Column: Nestle
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Worry about brand values has battered the shares of consumer products
companies. The once-dull Nestle, though, has emerged relatively unscathed.
Its geographic and product spread underscores its defensive attractions. But
the company has also been promoting its expansionist ambitions as it raises
SFr1.2bn of fresh equity and seeks a New York listing. US investors appear
especially attracted to Nestle, which contrasts with the seemingly secular
decline of their own food manufacturers. Nestle still appears to retain
considerable growth potential.
Since 1985, Nestle has spent Dollars 10bn on acquisitions which have yet to
bear full fruit. There may be scope for more. Philip Morris's determination
to defend its home turf in US tobacco may mean European food assets become
cheaper. Nestle's greatest volume growth is likely to come from developing
markets. It is well-placed in foods in the Far East and South America. While
European markets remain soft and US competition fierce Nestle seems likely
to bask in the sunshine. Unilever's shares, which have flagged recently, may
be better geared to recovery given its greater industrial interests.
</TEXT>
