<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 93 / Observer: Unfair competition
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
While Neil Kinnock struggles to carve out a new career as a disc
jockey-cum-game show celebrity, his former lieutenant Charles Clarke has
found a lucrative niche advising companies on how to dispense with the
costly services of professional lobbyists.
Most Westminster exiles end up as political lobbyists themselves, wining and
dining their former colleagues to promote clients' interests. Clarke, for
nearly 10 years Kinnock's chief of staff and leading 'fixer', has refused to
jump on that particular gravy train. His consultancy Quality Public Affairs
tells organisations how they can do their own lobbying more effectively for
a fraction of the cost. It's such a novel idea that it is probably only a
matter of time before Clarke gets an offer he can't refuse to sell out.
</TEXT>
