<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 93 / Letter: Essential safeguards before giving central bank
independence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Dr BRENDAN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, The suggested provisions for democratic accountability of an
independent central bank which Samuel Brittan set out (Economic Viewpoint,
June 17) omit two safeguards essential to a new, more liberal order. First,
its policymaking committee should operate under a well-specified freedom of
information code, which would be fully enforceable in law. Under the code,
both parliamentarians and the general public should have full access to all
background papers to policy decisions, and comprehensive minutes should be
published of policymaking meetings with minimal delay - including a record
of which way individual members voted.
Second, top-level appointments in the central bank must be subject to
approval of a parliamentary committee where members vote without
interference by party whips. Analogous to Senate ratification of Federal
Reserve appointments, members of the committee would cross-examine
candidates towards assessing their competence. Questions could be raised,
for example, as to the candidate's role in the Pounds 5bn estimated loss on
Black Wednesday, and his or her attitude towards previous monetary
decisions. Independence should not take effect until all positions on the
top policymaking committee, including present officials, have been ratified
accordingly.
Brendan Brown,
director and head of research,
Mitsubishi Finance
International,
6 Broadgate,
London EC2M 2AA
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6011 Federal Reserve Banks.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
