FT  21 JUN 93 / Letter: The CAB and employees' rights
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Ms ANN ABRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, I am writing to correct an inaccuracy in your report, 'Union
restrictions extended by new law' (June 18), which seriously misrepresents
the position of the Citizens Advice Bureaux Service. The CAB service, while
recommending that individual employment rights should be strengthened, has
never argued that this should supersede collective bargaining. The service
sees no contradiction between the role of collective bargaining and
strengthening individual employment rights.
When clients come to a CAB with an employment problem, they will be advised
to consult their trade union or staff association if they are members. This
is because the union or staff association will have detailed knowledge of
the employer's practices and will be able to represent the client most
effectively. Involvement of a trade union will almost always strengthen the
client's position. If the client is not in a trade union, or does not wish
to consult one, the CAB will always offer advice and representation as
appropriate.
Employment is now the third highest subject of inquiries to Citizens Advice
Bureaux. While some elements of the new legislation will undoubtedly be
beneficial to CAB clients, the service remains extremely concerned about a
number of provisions in the Trade Union Reform and Employment Rights Bill,
in particular the abolition of wages councils. In the absence of collective
bargaining in the sectors covered by wages councils, their abolition is
likely to result in a decrease in wages and increased dependence on social
security benefits, as was pointed out by your editorial 'Waging war'
(November 6 1992).
Ann Abraham,
chief executive,
Citizens Advice Bureau,
Myddelton House,
115-123 Pentonville Road,
London N1 9LZ
</TEXT>
