<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 93 / Survey of Nordic Banking and Finance (4): Shareholders show
support / Profile of Kansallis-Osake-Pankki
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN Mr Pertti Voutilainen took over as chief executive of
Kansallis-Osake-Pankki last year, his move from a state-owned mining group
to the private sector banking world prompted a student to ask what qualified
him for the job, writes Christopher Brown-Humes.
'My experience of running state-owned companies,' he replied.
The joke, which reflected on a growing state role in the rescue of Finland's
beleaguered banking sector, could easily have gone sour as the country's
leading commercial bank turned out to be in much worse shape than he
expected when he first arrived.
In 1992 it piled up a FM3.7bn deficit, more than double 1991's FM1.61bn
loss, after lending losses tripled to FM4.27bn from FM1.34bn. In August it
availed itself of a FM1.73bn injection of preference capital from the
government and by the end of the year it looked a clear candidate for a more
extensive state bail-out.
Since then, though, things have started to look up. Losses have begun to
show a declining trend, thanks to the steep fall in Finnish interest rates
since last autumn. Just as importantly, the bank has successfully raised
FM1bn through a rights issue, demonstrating strong shareholder support for
its efforts to solve its problems on its own and reducing the likelihood
that it will need to ask for state assistance.
The decisive move came in February when KOP announced plans to raise some
FM3bn through a rights issue and domestic and international debt issues. It
was the first bank in the region to ask shareholders to help it to weather
the financial crisis and there was widespread scepticism about its chances
of success given the broader difficulties within Finnish banking.
In fact, KOP not only raised the FM930m it was originally seeking, but it
marginally increased the size of the issue to FM1bn because of
over-subscription. Part of the reason for its success was the
almost-missionary zeal with which it appealed to small shareholders across
the land to 'save' the bank from state clutches.
Another important factor was the bank's increasingly optimistic tone about
its recovery prospects. Mr Voutilainen says he expects the bank's loss for
1993 to halve to about FM2bn, on the back of lower credit losses, with a
return to profit by 1995.
There has been some scepticism about these projections, with some analysts
predicting that the bank could still make a loss of FM3-3.5bn this year.
They draw attention to the depressed state of the domestic economy and say
credit losses from small and medium-sized businesses will still be huge.
Furthermore, loan losses in the municipal and household sectors are rising.
Mr Voutilainen cautions that the bank's recovery hinges on wider economic
recovery. 'The bank is sick because the economy of our country is sick,' he
says.
He also accepts that the bank needs to raise more capital to strengthen its
capital base, as losses continue to erode its 9 per cent international
capital adequacy ratio. The plan is to raise about FM2bn this year and next
through a series of domestic and international debt issues. A bond issue in
the domestic market to raise FM300m has already been launched and it is
expected to be supplemented by issues for a further FM500m-FM1bn later in
the year.
In addition, analysts believe the bank may launch another rights issue when
it believes the market can digest it.
The Finnish banking crisis has taken its toll on KOP in a number of ways. It
has forced rationalisation, with staff numbers being cut last year by 8 per
cent to 8,500. It has also led to a more focused international strategy,
with the emphasis now on treasury operations and the funding of domestic
clients abroad. Gone are the days when the group would readily build up a
FM200m exposure to an international property group such as Olympia &amp; York.
Inevitably the focus is much more on the domestic market, where KOP is
playing its part in the wider reshaping of the banking sector. Already this
year it has taken a significant step with a takeover of the country's
sixth-largest bank, STS, in a move which has boosted its presence in the
household sector and in the Helsinki region.
It has also held discussions with the state authorities about a takeover of
the two savings bank groups, Skopbank and the Savings Bank of Finland.
Such a move would give it a theoretical market share of 40 per cent and has
been resisted by the bank's competitors. In any case, Merrill Lynch has now
been called in to examine all options for the future of the two groups, so
the talks with KOP are on the back burner.
Mr Voutilainen says further restructuring in the banking sector is
inevitable in a country which is 'over-branched if not over-banked.' Of the
main banks which today command a nationwide network - KOP, Unitas,
Postipankki, Okobank and the savings banks - he believes at least one and
possibly two will disappear.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Kansallis-Osake-Pankki.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>FIZ  Finland, West Europe.
</CN>
